{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c0d67c53-a565-4e78-8494-a86ae52b83d7","content":"Use `dotnet watch` to automatically re-run tests on every file save:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThis watches for changes to `InventoryServiceTests.cs`, rebuilds, and re-runs just that one test. The `--filter` keeps the feedback loop tight.\n\n**The bug:** `RemoveStock` subtracts without checking if there's enough stock. It should throw when `quantity > available`. For example, fix line 37:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply the fix so you can verify it with `dotnet watch`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07811614-721c-46cb-9cf6-d7c5e7bedcbb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and MSTest using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to automatically re-run tests when files change.\n\nLet me check what's available. Since they're using .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test --hotreload` might be available, or they can use `dotnet watch test`.\n\nThe standard approach is `dotnet watch test` which watches for file changes and re-runs tests.\n\nLet me just show them how to use `dotnet watch test` - that's the simplest hot reload approach for tests.","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"3418:24F9C3:B7B81E:D71EC1:69F4048A"},"id":"0dbe0941-c522-48fa-9338-4754c5a45486","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:40:35.584Z","parentId":"df9406c2-7305-4a59-9080-f1442abc70c6"}
